fields.project_description: Orcasound is a network that connects live hydrophones (underwater microphones) monitoring the habitat of endangered orcas with citizen scientists, educational environmental non-profits, and machine learning algorithms. The web-based Orcasound app (launched November 1, 2018) makes it easy to listen for whales -- both for their amazing orca sounds and for noise that may be detrimental to them -- by using HTTP Live Streaming (and eventually MPEG-DASH). These formats optimize playback performance over a wide range of browser/device combinations within the Orcasound web-app that plays a live audio stream. [The backend is an Elixir app using the Phoenix framework. The Phoenix app serves a React app.]
fields.project_description_solution:
The Orcasound app at live.orcasound.net enables citizen scientists to monitor the acoustic environment of the whales and report when they hear the orcas call, whistle, or click, or when they hear other interesting signals. At the same time, machine learning classifiers work on lossless uncompressed data that is also transmitted to AWS S3 buckets from each hydrophone. Synergy between human and machine detection and classification will not only facilitate basic research into the communication and echolocation systems of fish-eating killer whales and other local marine species, but also will enhance many other research and educational activities to help the orcas recover. 

Notifications from the app when orca sounds are detected support: direct conservation actions by the listeners; live-listening events and associated outreach activities at the educational facilities of Orcasound members; NOAA studies of orca health and diet; mitigation of human-caused noise -- like pile driving at Wash
fields.project_description_actions:
Thus, to help save the endangered southern resident killer whales, we need a wide spectrum of volunteers: developers (for software -- at the hydrophone node, in the app, and for real-time cloud-based data analysis), beta-tester citizen scientists, user researchers, designers, and data hackers. Hackathon challenges include: optimize low-latency audio data acquisition and the upload script on the Raspberry Pi to improve player performance in the app; prioritize key features for beta-testing and implement a cycle of testing and refining them; develop an administrative interface (login, CMS, detection moderation, notifications); integrate a map view of hydrophone locations into the UI; clarify and begin implementing machine learning architecture and data pipelines; test mechanisms for real-time analysis, including visualization of audio data as a spectrogram, annotations from human or machine classifications, and quantification of noise statistics.

Check out our public roadmap (Trello boa
fields.project_short_description: Open source web-app (at live.orcasound.net ) that lets users listen for whales and act to conserve them.

fields.project_description:
The Banana App is a tech initiative of the Be Good Project in an effort to help alleviate poverty by preventing unintentional hunger and reducing food wastage. 

The United States wastes 150,000 tons of food each day – equal to a pound per person. Up to 40 percent of the food in the United States is never eaten. But at the same time, one in eight Americans struggles to put enough food on the table - NRDC

In 2015, according to the USDA, Americas threw away 133 billion pounds of food worth $161 billion, which equates almost 220 lbs per person. Wasted food is the single largest category of material placed in municipal landfills and represents nourishment that could have helped feed families in need. Additionally, water, energy, and labor used to produce wasted food could have been employed for other purposes.  – fda
fields.project_description_solution: Even though these levels are alarming, a lot of opportunities still exist to help farms, supermarkets and restaurants rescue food from being misallocated, misplaced and even misused. And that's why the Banana App is here!
fields.project_description_actions: Our mobile-based project "Banana App" will provide supermarkets/groceries/produce-stands/restaurants a time-sensitive platform to donate bananas/produce/foods that are considered not aesthetically-pleasing for market display or sale but still edible and in good condition. Verified no-to-low-income clients/homeless individuals will be able to register using our app. Upon completion and approval of the application, user can accept and pickup these donations.
fields.project_short_description: UberEats/Postmates/Foursquare-like App for food donations.

fields.project_description:
Do you think there can be a more constructive way forward with the issue of climate change? Do you think the world's communities and cultures can learn something from each other? 

More specifically, what if people had a platform for sharing climate solutions, the same way programmers have GitHub, StackOverflow, and web forums for sharing coding solutions? 

We all recognize the problem of climate change and know general ideas for solutions - the difficult problem is implementing those solutions, in context and at scale, with all available nuance. ClimateTree.wiki is an innovative project that empowers communities, students, and activists to find the specific climate solutions that are right for their own place.
fields.project_description_solution: The data base architecture ("back end") will be comprised of unique geographic place names of all sizes (village to province to nation) with attributes of geographic data like population, bioregion, renewable energy, and carbon emissions. This back end will allow a UX wherein the user can dynamically filter the database for subset extracts -- much the way Zillow does with real estate. There is room here for additional visualization UX that can interactively visualize this back end data on a map or chart.
fields.project_description_actions:
Ultimately, all content will have "geographic place name tags" and "thematic tags". From this structure, many UX ideas are possible. We will pursue the one that will get us a Tweet from Greta Thunberg or Leonardo DiCaprio and spread among all students and activists striking for climate change. 

More locally, the City of Olympia, Washington, has passed a climate action plan at the behest of high school students - the question is ...now what? That's where ClimateTree.wiki comes in. With this toolset, instead of a cry for help, students will be able to surface detailed, effective options that in many cases have been implemented elsewhere.
fields.project_short_description: Empowering students and communities to research, share, and discuss geographically and culturally relevant climate solution strategies

fields.project_description: Nearly one in four people in Washington State have been involved in the criminal justice system. Washington recently enacted the New Hope Act that makes it easier for people with past criminal records to have their convictions vacated. Conviction vacation removes significant barriers to housing and employment, improving the chances of successful reentry into society and making recidivism less likely.
fields.project_description_solution: We analyzed the process of conviction vacation in Washington state, and have identified opportunities to use technology to streamline the process. Our efforts at the National Day of Civic Hacking on September 21st focused on automating eligibility calculation for conviction vacation. We see future opportunity to streamline the completion of the required forms. We are investigating the feasibility of a Turbo Tax style interface to simplify this process, and then e-filing the forms in counties where it is permitted.
fields.project_description_actions: We need researchers to further explore workflows and user requirements,  designers to help create the interface, and developers to build it. Take a look at the working prototype that's been built (in the project links section of this page), and hop into the #conviction-vacation-project channel using the Slack link. Finally, click "Volunteer With Project" above so we can get you listed here as a team member!
fields.project_short_description: Reducing barriers faced by formerly incarcerated individuals by streamlining process of vacating eligible convictions in Washington state.

fields.project_description: We wondered why it was so hard to find out what is happening in Seattle City Council for a specific topic, so we set out to solve that. Let's make city councils actions and activities more discoverable. The first step to this is basic data processing: automated transcript creation for city council events, indexing those transcripts, and finally making them available on the web via our website and database.
fields.project_description_solution: Our Seattle infrastructure has now been up and running for about four months and are planning to deploy the same services for Bellevue city council with more cities coming in the future.
fields.project_description_actions: But what more can we do? Add more cities to the system? What about visualizations about topics covered by the city council? How about building predictive models for city council decisions and actions? Or even, summarizing city council member positions on topics? All of these and more are projects we are curious about, but if you have your own ideas we are glad to hear them.
fields.project_short_description: Empowering citizens and journalists to make city council activities discoverable and understandable by more than just legislators.

fields.project_description: Seattle traffic is getting worse. The current infrastructure often favors driving, with lots of push-back against proposals to reduce on-street parking, establish bus and bike lanes, and prioritize pedestrian crosswalk timers. There are lots of opportunities for small improvements to walking, biking, and transit, but no easy way to prototype or communicate them.
fields.project_description_solution: A/B Street is a tool to model Seattle's traffic infrastructure in detail -- including sidewalks, turn lanes, on- and off-street parking, traffic signals, etc -- and to simulate cars, bikes, buses, and pedestrians moving through it. Players can reallocate existing road space (convert a general car lane to a bus lane) and edit intersections (convert a traffic signal to have a pedestrian-only scramble cycle), then run a detailed A/B test to explore the impact on all agents. If a player's edits work well in A/B Street, then they could be proposed to SDOT to try in real life -- all of the edits would be cheap to prototype for a few days, not requiring lots of construction. The tool could also be used for SDOT to communicate proposals and alternatives to the public, letting people interactively visualize a change, rather than interpret static diagrams.
fields.project_description_actions:
I've been developing A/B Street for about 1.5 years, and I could use help with many areas. Upcoming work:

- new challenge modes to optimize a bus route, create greenways and superblocks, and detour around construction

- improve data visualization

- better heuristics for determining the traffic signal timings currently used

- importing bike trails like the Burke Gilman from OpenStreetMap, and improving the shared pedestrian/bike lane modeling

- improving the map geometry inferred from OpenStreetMap (complex intersections involving dual carriageways particularly need attention)
fields.project_short_description: A/B Street is a game simulating pedestrians, bikes, cars, and buses in Seattle. Players edit lanes and intersections to improve traffic flow

fields.project_description:
Millions of Washingtonians interact with state government each year. From using our transportation infrastructure, visiting a local department of Licensing office, visiting agency websites, calling or visiting agency offices for help navigating systems and programs, to opening a business, hiring employees. That’s just the short list.

Results Washington, Governor Inslee’s performance management and process improvement agency, is embarking on a strategy to make government more human.

Washington State is a leader in using data to drive decision making and policies. But there is a gap in qualitative data and understanding customer’s needs, motivations, behaviors. Many agencies do routine customer satisfaction surveys – which illuminate pain points and successes – but don’t provide enough information about the why, or who we are serving.
fields.project_description_solution:
Surveys don’t equal empathy. Or understanding.

The Idea: Feedback Friend
The concept is to provide a way to capture real-time feedback and experiences from both customers and employees around the state.

We’d like to explore the viability and feasibility of the idea.  The initial idea was to use voice and video recordings from mobile devices readily available to customers and employees. We’d like to understand how we could quickly design a pilot with a few locations around the state. We could also market the tool to all Washingtonians, not to just those with a recent in-office interaction.

Advice on building a business strategy and process flow would also be helpful. We are wondering if MS Dynamics could be good fit for the first version – it could be an experiment to inform a broader CRM solution.
fields.project_description_actions:
We are all-in and ready to experiment to find a way to really hear and understand our customers and employees.

Here are some initial questions we have about the idea.

How could:
+We use speech to text to capture feedback that can be easily analyzed? 
+Feedback be a source of actionable data, in the form of experiences, to lead to better understanding of needs and improved service delivery?
+The solution predict experiences?
+We use video, Real World confessional style, to give customers an opportunity to quickly share their experience?
fields.project_short_description: We need to hear from Washingtonians. We need to listen to and deeply understand our customers.

fields.project_description:
Room For Good is a service that connects home providers located in expensive cities, who have extra space, with essential workers who serve the city thrive but can't afford to live there. 

Social workers and city workers have jobs and a salary but still can not afford to live in the city where they work. 
Some homeowners have space but don't want to deal with unvetted rental services, would be open to good tenants, and... some also want to help the city thrive! 

(Think Airbnb UI / profiles and socially conscious communities rather than transient tourism) 
Sidebar: I have pitched to Jenny Durkin and she loves the idea! Cities, Non profits and workers are the primary stakeholders.
fields.project_short_description: Room For Good is a timely solution addressing the housing crisis in expensive cities!

fields.project_description:
This initiative comes from the Washington Tech Industry Association's (WTIA) Ion Collaboration, where professionals from the private, nonprofit, and government sectors come together to solve civic problems. 

Our proposed idea is to make technology more accessible for underrepresented communities in the South Seattle area. Specifically, we're aiming to use the untapped volunteer workforce in the tech community to help fuel the growth of immigrant/minority businesses. Our idea is to develop a platform that can showcase the tech needs (website development, delivery service integration, etc) of South Seattle businesses, thereby allowing tech volunteers to sign-up and develop the solutions.
fields.project_description_solution:
Users of the Platform:

Community Development Advocates (CDA) 
Conduit connecting businesses with the platform. Owner Of Relationship between biz and tech volunteers post-match. 

Technical Advocates (TA)
Conduit connecting volunteer with platform. Maintain database of volunteers and manage accountability of those volunteers.

Businesses
Key client. Final approver. Partners with Volunteer/TA on design reviews and final approval. 

Volunteers
Provide SOW execute on design with revisions inclusive. 

MVP Requirements
Businesses/CDA need a platform profile. 
Businesses/CDA need to be able to select from predefined use cases.
Businesses/CDA need to be able to provide contact info in a form inclusive of selected use cases
Volunteers/TA need to be able to select an ask. 
TAs need to be able to manage Volunteer database.
fields.project_short_description: Connecting immigrant and POC business owners with skilled tech volunteers

fields.project_description: We are a small nonprofit, nonpartisan pro-democracy organization in WA State working on reforms that strengthen democracy. Our mission is to achieve fair elections and government policies that reflect the will of the people and not the power of money. We focus on issues such as: campaign finance reform and money in elections; alternative voting systems, such as ranked choice voting; expanding voting access with things like automatic voter registration and same-day registration; as well as civic engagement and outreach to further help empower the people.
fields.project_description_solution: In order to help accomplish our mission, which have some lofty goals, we need a better website and way to engage our database and volunteers more efficiently and productively. We have very limited funds and capacity and are looking to find some qualified, creative, and passionate people to help us out.
fields.project_description_actions: We envision a website where people can easily find information about our organization, the democracy related reforms happening locally and nationally, how to support us, engage volunteers better, and spur people into action with the ability to do routine follow-up. In particular we need help with basic overview of what we already have, how we can develop it further, integrate our database more effectively, and what is needed to accomplish this.
fields.project_short_description: We need help redesigning our website & integrating our database, to better engage volunteers & the public about democracy reforms.

fields.project_description: Arguments and public debates are scattered across often hundreds of sources, op-eds, and editorials. This impairs deliberation, understanding, advocacy, and decision-making. The public-debate needs centralizing and visual framing. We have mastered this approach over a decade. We now want to apply various technologies, including potentially NLP and machine learning, to assist in the wide-scale aggregation and framing of public debates.
fields.project_description_solution: Centralize unique pro and con arguments and quotes into an ideal pro/con splitscreen and sub-debate structure to enhance deliberations. Utilize the latest technologies to assist this aggregation and framing. While we had attempted to use wiki technology on Debatepedia.org (which I founded in 2006) to address the scalability of this aggregation challenge, it failed for a few reasons. We are hoping other approaches, including NLP (or anything you might suggest), can provide the necessary breakthrough.
fields.project_description_actions: Develop unique solutions for aggregating and framing pro/con arguments and quotes in public debates around the country and world. NLP and machine learning are one promising avenue. There may be others. Any other inspired actions/suggestions around the concept of IssueCounsel.com are more than welcomed.
fields.project_short_description: Aggregating the world’s arguments into the ideal pro/con visual framework for deliberation, communications, & advocacy (Debatepedia.org 2.0)

fields.project_description: Seattle residents rely on government and nonprofit technology to access key information and resources, like utility accounts, housing assistance, permits, and library services. But residents may not always be consulted during the process of building that technology. This can lead to low adoption, usability issues, and the creation of digital resources that don't actually solve community needs.
fields.project_description_solution: This feedback can come anywhere in the development process, from initial planning stages to design feedback to usability testing. In this way, residents have a voice and a role in building civic technology.
fields.project_description_actions:
Residents are paid to participate, and government agencies, nonprofits, and civic tech developers can use the Civic User Testing Group as a free service. 

The CUTGroup is a partnership between Open Seattle, the University of Washington Information School, and the City of Seattle Department of Information Technology.
fields.project_short_description: Seattle’s Civic User Testing Group (CUTGroup) connects nonprofits and civic developers with Seattle residents to get their feedback.

fields.project_description:
Civic Space helps local authorities make more informed decisions. We constantly collect and analyze the comments, ideas and suggestions of each citizen of the platform. Our software for civic participation enables local governments to take advantage of the collective minds of citizens and better understand the needs of their citizens.
We believe that with the Civic Space platform, we will give the public the opportunity to influence socially-minded decisions, to engage in joint policy-making with the municipal authorities.
fields.project_short_description: Digital participatory democracy platform for cities and organizations

fields.project_description:
The mission of Open Source Ecology (OSE) is to create the open source economy.

An open source, libre economy is an efficient economy which increases innovation by open collaboration. To get there, OSE is currently developing a set of open source blueprints for the Global Village Construction Set (GVCS) – a set of the 50 most important machines that it takes for modern life to exist – everything from a tractor, to an oven, to a circuit maker. In the process of creating the GVCS, OSE intends to develop a modular, scalable platform for documenting and developing open source, libre hardware – including blueprints for both physical artifacts and for related open enterprises.

The current practical implementation of the GVCS is a life size LEGO set of powerful, self-replicating production tools for distributed production. The Set includes fabrication and automated machines that make other machines.
fields.project_description_solution:
We – the countless collaborators upon whose shoulders this Vision stands – imagine a world of innovation accelerated by open, collaborative development – to solve wicked problems – before they are created. We see a world of prosperity that doesn’t leave anyone behind. We see a world of interdisciplinary, synergistic systems thinking – not the isolated silos of today’s world.

This work of distributing raw productive power to people is not only a means to solving wicked problems – but a means for humans themselves to evolve. The creation of a new world depends on expansion of human consciousness and personal evolution – as individuals tap their autonomy, mastery, and purpose – bo Build Themselves – and to become responsible for the world around them. One outcome is a world beyond artificial material scarcity – where no longer do material constraints and resource conflicts dictate most of human interactions – personal and political.
fields.project_description_actions: The end point of our practical development is Distributive Enterprise – an open, collaborative enterprise that publishes all of its strategic, business, organizational, enterprise information – so that others could learn and thereby truly accelerate innovation by annihilating all forms of competitive waste. We see this as the only way to solve wicked problems faster than they are created – a struggle worth the effort. In the age where companies spend more on patent protectionism than on research and development – we feel that unleashing the power of collaborative innovation is an idea whose time has come.
fields.project_short_description: We’re developing open source industrial machines that can be made for a fraction of commercial costs. We share our designs online for free.

fields.project_description:
#Newsrooms is a startup that is building a news platform that provides news in a better way and helps users better consume those news articles.
 
We recently ran an extensive experiment testing the effect of #Newsrooms' algorithm, and we found out that #Newsrooms’ readers acquired significantly more knowledge from news articles in a more efficient way compared to users of other news platforms such as Google News. More balanced (less polarized) news consumption was also achieved. (see https://drive.google.com/open?id=13KgTgP0X3Qd10Tt7h7R6mGDojie65OuE for more detailed experimental method and results)
fields.project_description_solution: We are looking for NLP engineers who can realize the algorithm that we have in mind in order to solve various fundamental journalistic problems and significantly refine existing platforms. This NLP script will be trained with AI later on.
fields.project_description_actions: The specific solution will be discussed when you decide to work with us. We recently ran an extensive experiment testing the effect of #Newsrooms' algorithm, and we found out that #Newsrooms’ readers acquired significantly more knowledge from news articles in a more efficient way compared to users of other news platforms such as Google News. More balanced (less polarized) news consumption was also achieved.
fields.project_short_description: #Newsrooms aims to build a news platform that provides news in a better way and helps users better consume those news articles.

fields.project_description: Non profits don’t usually have sufficient resources to promote the wonderful work they do in their communities. At the same time, they spend majority of the time looking for funding to stay alive.
fields.project_description_solution: Donors on the other side aren’t usually aware of all the non profits that serve in communities they live in or the causes they care deeply about.
fields.project_description_actions: Our platform would provide non profits a place to portray their work in the best possible manner while the donors are able to determine which non profit is serving in the neighborhoods they wish to support.
fields.project_short_description: Platform that allows nonprofits to portray their work & donors to connect with nonprofits in the neighborhoods they wish to support.
